<div id="review_3380962587" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3380962587" />
    <a title="Laura Anne" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/55478778-laura-anne"><img alt="Laura Anne" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1462205788p2/55478778.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3380962587?book_show_action=true">Jun 10, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laura Anne" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laura Anne" href="/user/show/55478778-laura-anne">Laura Anne</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780571175482" href="/book/show/822519.Death_In_The_Andes">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3380962587" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14642516839019949375">I kept reading this...and reading this â€¦ and I kept thinking &apos;when&apos;s it going to get better or interesting?&apos; And I have given up - page 209. There is none of the magic that I found in &apos;Who Killed Palomino Molero?&apos; - which is strange because we have the same character of officer Lituma - now Corporal and a similar junior - Tomasito. We have the Andes; we have political background - which is violent, nasty, sickening - and yet because the violence is carried out to characters who are not participa</span>
  <span id="freeText14642516839019949375" style="display:none">I kept reading this...and reading this â€¦ and I kept thinking 'when's it going to get better or interesting?' And I have given up - page 209. There is none of the magic that I found in 'Who Killed Palomino Molero?' - which is strange because we have the same character of officer Lituma - now Corporal and a similar junior - Tomasito. We have the Andes; we have political background - which is violent, nasty, sickening - and yet because the violence is carried out to characters who are not participants in the two main stories - we are not - involved - for lack of a better word.<br /><br />So this is the great Mario Vargas Llosa? The back cover says 'Unputdownable and unforgettable â€¦ ' Is 'unput...etc. a word?<br /><br />'He is a great storyteller, who combines high seriousness with lightness of touch, and this is without doubt another of his great stories.' <b>The Times</b>'. Absolute bollocks!<br /><br />And let's not blame the translator - the lethargy, the winding long-windedness, distracted telling - is an experiment - gone wrong. I felt the author needed to make a statement about his country - as if he was washing his hands of the whole ugly situation - a bit like Pontius Pilate.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14642516839019949375" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


