    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3793368720" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3793368720" />
    <a title="Lorna" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6700518-lorna"><img alt="Lorna" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1627226385p2/6700518.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3793368720?book_show_action=true">Feb 28, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lorna" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lorna" href="/user/show/6700518-lorna">Lorna</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/11733485-death-in-the-andes">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6700518-lorna?shelf=latin-america">latin-america</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6700518-lorna?shelf=mystery-thriller">mystery-thriller</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6700518-lorna?shelf=political-history">political-history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6700518-lorna?shelf=nobel-prize">nobel-prize</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6700518-lorna?shelf=magical-realism">magical-realism</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3793368720" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14347581586057084440"><i>Death in the Andes</i> was an intense historical fiction account of the period in Peru when the Communist Party of Peru - Shining Path known in Spanish as <i>Sendero Luminoso</i>, a terrorist organization that rose to prominence in 1980 with its goal being the overthrow of the state by guerilla warfare and replacing it with a <i>Maoist</i>-type of government. This rebel group terrorized the nation for the next twenty to twenty-five years, brutally murdering people with many others just disappearing without a trac</span>
  <span id="freeText14347581586057084440" style="display:none"><i>Death in the Andes</i> was an intense historical fiction account of the period in Peru when the Communist Party of Peru - Shining Path known in Spanish as <i>Sendero Luminoso</i>, a terrorist organization that rose to prominence in 1980 with its goal being the overthrow of the state by guerilla warfare and replacing it with a <i>Maoist</i>-type of government. This rebel group terrorized the nation for the next twenty to twenty-five years, brutally murdering people with many others just disappearing without a trace. Peruvian author Mario Vargas Llosa was awarded The Nobel Prize in Literature in 2010. While this is the first of his books that I have read, I certainly am looking forward to reading more of his works as I enjoy Latin American literature. It is said that in the 1960s there was a rapid interest and development in Latin American literature with Mario Vargas Llosa at the heart of this movement with his ardent love of storytelling characterized by his use of rich language.<br /><br />In the riveting narrative, <i>Death in the Andes,</i> Corporal Lituma has been transferred as punishment to the tiny community of Naccos, nestled high in the Andes, with his adjutant Tomas Carreno to investigate the disappearance of three men from the village. The question was whether this was due to the terrorists of the <i>Maoist Shining Path</i> or something more ominous responsible for the vanishing of these three villagers. While the novel examines the tactics and motivations of the Maoist terrorists, it is within the backdrop of the context of an older world where life is brutal and on the fringes of modern society. Mario Vargas Llosa uses a lot of magical realism to explore the old Incan and Indian spirituality and beliefs, including frequent references to <i>pishtacos,</i> Andean vampires in ancient Peruvian folklore. What enfolds is a very powerful story.<br /><br /><i>"The sun was going down, and a sumptuous peacock's tail opened along the horizon. An expanse of dark green flatland on their left, with no trees, no houses, no people or animals, was brightened by watery flashes, as if there might be streams or lagoons among the clumps of yellow straw. On the right, however, there rose a a craggy, perpendicular of towering rocks, chasms and gorges."</i><br /><br /><i>"In the fading light they could still make out the vast expanse around them, with its patchwork of cultivated fields and a terrain that grew stonier as it rose and disappeared into the clouds."</i><br /><br /><i>"Lituma could see a rainbow crowning the hills around the camp, hovering over the eucalyptus grove. The ground, covered with puddles and gleaming rivulets, looked like quicksilver. And along the horizon, along the Cordillera where rock and sky met, there was that strange color, somewhere between violet and purple, which he had seen reproduced on so many Indian skirts and shawls and on the woolen bags the campesinos hung from the ears of their llamas; for him it was the color of the Andes, of this mysterious, violent sierra."</i><br /><br /><i>"Like pisco, music helps us understand bitter truths."</i><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14347581586057084440" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


