<span id="freeTextContainer1239267095135568556">The old mingles with the new in Vargas Llosaâ€™s Peru. Human sacrifices and spirits of the mountains, road building, terrucos â€“ uncompromising, ruthless and cruel freedom fighters coming out of nowhere and conducting their cruel people trials, and superstitious mountain people (serruchos) are the backdrop for the plot and its main characters. Captain Lituma and his adjutant Tomasito, people from the new, more modern world, are posted in a remote mountain village to guard the road building against </span>
  <span id="freeText1239267095135568556" style="display:none">The old mingles with the new in Vargas Llosaâ€™s Peru. Human sacrifices and spirits of the mountains, road building, terrucos â€“ uncompromising, ruthless and cruel freedom fighters coming out of nowhere and conducting their cruel people trials, and superstitious mountain people (serruchos) are the backdrop for the plot and its main characters. Captain Lituma and his adjutant Tomasito, people from the new, more modern world, are posted in a remote mountain village to guard the road building against the terrucos. The terrucos donâ€™t attack them, yet three people go missing without a trace. Captain Lituma is obsessively trying to piece what happened to them. At the same time his adjutant, Tomasito, canâ€™t stop thinking about Mercedes, a prostitute he has fallen in love with and for whom he is longing. Tradition and superstition, death, love and obsession interweave and drive the plot in this tale. <br /><br />It was very well written, and I loved the style. I found the world portrayed sinister yet fascinating.</span>
