<div id="review_2166456868" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2166456868" />
    <a title="Robert Gammon" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/62176913-robert-gammon"><img alt="Robert Gammon" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1606989069p2/62176913.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2166456868?book_show_action=true">Mar 18, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Robert Gammon" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Robert Gammon" href="/user/show/62176913-robert-gammon">Robert Gammon</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2166456868" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14344648881533825039">Death in the Andes (Spanish title: Lituma en los Andes)<br/><br/>This novel by Peruvian Nobel Prize winner Mario Vargas Llosa won the prestigious Planeta literary award in 1993. It is set in the midst of a virtual civil war that took place in his native Peru between 1980 and 2000, leaving 70,000 people dead. The conflict was between the Shining Path maoist guerrillas and the Peruvian armed forces and anti-maoist peasant groups. Both sides were accused of terrible atrocities. Vargas Llosa was directly invo</span>
  <span id="freeText14344648881533825039" style="display:none">Death in the Andes (Spanish title: Lituma en los Andes)<br /><br />This novel by Peruvian Nobel Prize winner Mario Vargas Llosa won the prestigious Planeta literary award in 1993. It is set in the midst of a virtual civil war that took place in his native Peru between 1980 and 2000, leaving 70,000 people dead. The conflict was between the Shining Path maoist guerrillas and the Peruvian armed forces and anti-maoist peasant groups. Both sides were accused of terrible atrocities. Vargas Llosa was directly involved as the Peruvian President appointed him to head a commission to investigate the assassination of eight journalists in 1983. In 1990, Vargas Llosa himself would narrowly lose the Peruvian Presidential elections.<br /><br />The novel depicts the atmosphere of fear in the Peruvian Andes at the time, with the Shining Path guerrillas controlling large areas of the countryside and descending on villages. After improvised, so-called peopleÂ´s trials (on anyone deemed contrary to them, with villagers accusing each other sometimes out of spite), those â€œguiltyâ€ were stoned to death in front of fellow villagers. Guerrillas would recruit men, young women and even children to carry out these terrible deeds. Vargas Llosa depicts this in two chapters of the novel where guerrillas stop a bus and murder two young French travelers (spuriously accused of being â€œthe enemyâ€), and execute a well-known environmentalist working on an NGO reforestation project for the benefit of the Andean people the guerrillas claim to be fighting for. <br /><br />Vargas Llosa does a masterful job of taking the reader into this nightmarish scenario. His two main characters are two policemen (Corporal Lituma and his assistant, TomÃ¡s CarreÃ±o) in a lonely Andean outpost, in constant fear of Shining Path guerrillas arriving and the policemen not standing a chance to survive. The author also introduces us to Andean Indian culture, superstitions and harsh life as the background to three assassinations that Lituma diligently tries to investigate. The novel also reveals entrenched prejudices between Peruvians from the coast (like Lituma) and those from the Andes.<br /><br />During the cold and lonely nights in their shack, TomÃ¡s tells Lituma the story of his affair with Mercedes, a prostitute he rescued from a drug dealer (leading to him being posted to this isolated location). With nothing else to keep them from boredom, Lituma encourages TomÃ¡s to pour his heart out.<br /><br />Lituma is a character that first appeared in one of the authorÂ´s first novels in 1966: The Green House.<br /><br />With all the foregoing historical background and the authorâ€™s skill at weaving plots together into a coherent story, this novel is an excellent read. However, I would say that this novel is more plot driven than character driven, compared to other novels by Vargas Llosa, where the strength of his characters is often a greater allure for readers. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14344648881533825039" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


