<div id="review_1997232506" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1997232506" />
    <a title="Alexandra" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3977781-alexandra"><img alt="Alexandra" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1602719655p2/3977781.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1997232506?book_show_action=true">Jul 22, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alexandra" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alexandra" href="/user/show/3977781-alexandra">Alexandra</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3977781-alexandra?shelf=peru-literature">peru-literature</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1997232506" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15998920507250306453">&quot;Death in the Andes&quot; is the first book I&apos;ve read by Mario Vargas Llosa, the Peruvian Nobel Prize winner. It will not be the last.<br/><br/>The book follows Corporal Lituma (who I gather is the main character of a number of Llosa novels), a police officer assigned to a poor community in the midst of building a road high up in the Andes. The book is set during the days of terror of the Shining Path, a Maoist terrorist organization that killed many people in Peru primarily in the 1980s. Lituma is investigati</span>
  <span id="freeText15998920507250306453" style="display:none">"Death in the Andes" is the first book I've read by Mario Vargas Llosa, the Peruvian Nobel Prize winner. It will not be the last.<br /><br />The book follows Corporal Lituma (who I gather is the main character of a number of Llosa novels), a police officer assigned to a poor community in the midst of building a road high up in the Andes. The book is set during the days of terror of the Shining Path, a Maoist terrorist organization that killed many people in Peru primarily in the 1980s. Lituma is investigating the disappearances of three men from the town. Are their disappearances related to the Shining Path? Or is it something to do with the tense atmosphere of the town?<br /><br />Mysticism pervades the book. It was fascinating to read about pishtacos, the Peruvian version of vampires, and other elements of Peruvian folklore. Lituma may be skeptical of such things, but other characters believe. <br /><br />The secondary characters are well drawn - the lovelorn Tomas, pining for his beautiful Mercedes; the aptly named Dionisio and his sinister wife (or maenad) Adriana; and the victims of the Shining Path whose deaths we witness, including a hapless young French couple and a self-righteous ecologist. I found Lituma to be the least interesting character; perhaps if I had read Llosa's other Lituma works first, I would have understood Lituma's character better. I especially found Lituma's homophobia to be jarring, since he's the protoganist. I'm not sure what Llosa was trying to say with this (especially as he is an advocate for LGBT rights in South America). <br /><br />The best part of the book is the writing. Even in translation, Llosa's beautiful prose and narrative style comes through. He effortlessly weaves together separate stories and narratives in a single paragraphs - a most unusual style. <br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[I liked the ending, with its contrast of Tomas's happy ending and Lituma's horror at learning the truth of what happened to the three men. An appropriate end to a book that is a mix of violence, love, and terror. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
  <a data-text-id="15998920507250306453" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

