  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_179639104" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/179639104" />
    <a title="Marvin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2160536-marvin"><img alt="Marvin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1485672728p2/2160536.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/179639104?book_show_action=true">Jun 25, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marvin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marvin" href="/user/show/2160536-marvin">Marvin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer179639104" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7903521792487021143"><i>Death in the Andes</i> is ostensibly a mystery. Three men are missing in an impoverished Andean mining town. This is originally blamed on the Senderistas, a vicious Communist guerrilla group that terrorized Peru in the 80s. However, when Civil Guards Lituma and Carreno investigate, they suggest there may be older and more disturbing forces at work. But Llosa is not so interested in the mystery as much as to chronicle the history of violence in modern Peru as well as its ancient sources. There is no </span>
  <span id="freeText7903521792487021143" style="display:none"><i>Death in the Andes</i> is ostensibly a mystery. Three men are missing in an impoverished Andean mining town. This is originally blamed on the Senderistas, a vicious Communist guerrilla group that terrorized Peru in the 80s. However, when Civil Guards Lituma and Carreno investigate, they suggest there may be older and more disturbing forces at work. But Llosa is not so interested in the mystery as much as to chronicle the history of violence in modern Peru as well as its ancient sources. There is no question that the "Shining Path" guerrillas were as brutal as a group can be. However Llosa does not excuse also the excesses of the Peruvian army nor the ritualistic history of the Peruvian people. The most unusual aspect of this novel is the deft way Llosa handles past and present. He weaves them together often within the same few paragraph. This elicits a disorienting feeling in the reader not unlike the PTSD flashback of a trauma survivor. I think this is purely intentional. One of the lighter parts of the book, and there are not too many of them, involves the nightly retelling by Carreno of his eternal love of a prostitute in which Lituma continues a commentary in present day woven in the telling of the past. It is a virtuoso move exhibiting why Llosa became the surprise winner of the 2010 Nobel Prize in Literature. <br /><br />Yet, Llosa loses a certain continuity in the novel. He moves around from atrocity to atrocity, shocking the reader but never grounding them and allowing to gauge their full feelings for the events. The abundance of characters also makes this tale hard to follow and to assimilate. At the end you are stunned by the virtuosity of the writer but not as involved in this tragic story as you might be. Nonetheless, it is a powerful novel just missing the five star level and it will certainly lead me to read more by this Peruvian author.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7903521792487021143" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

