  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/405697566" />
    <a title="Erin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12441316-erin"><img alt="Erin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1578088478p2/12441316.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/405697566?book_show_action=true">Sep 02, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Erin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Erin" href="/user/show/12441316-erin">Erin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780312427252" href="/book/show/337930.Death_in_the_Andes">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer405697566" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15546896306250553174">The most fascinating part of the novel for me was the way Vargas Llosa plays with time and space as he tells various, intersecting stories. I have never experienced a writer who could accomplish telling a story in two different moments simultaneously in such a flawless way. <br/><br/>The novel begins with some gritty stories of naive travelers who fall victim to Sendero Luminoso revolutionaries and then transitions into an exploration of the more sinister elements of indigenous cosmovision, including the </span>
  <span id="freeText15546896306250553174" style="display:none">The most fascinating part of the novel for me was the way Vargas Llosa plays with time and space as he tells various, intersecting stories. I have never experienced a writer who could accomplish telling a story in two different moments simultaneously in such a flawless way. <br /><br />The novel begins with some gritty stories of naive travelers who fall victim to Sendero Luminoso revolutionaries and then transitions into an exploration of the more sinister elements of indigenous cosmovision, including the evil spirits of the mountains (apus) and human fat eating vampires living in caves (pishtacos). <br /><br />The "mystery" of three dissapeared men in the Andean highlands of Peru is interwoven with a young cop's story of falling in love with a prostitute, which was another well told thread of the story. Just as it provides a much needed distraction for the two cops who are investigating the disappearences in the mountains, it also provides a diversion for the reader from the darkness of the story. <br /><br />I started reading this book on a return trip from Mexico and read the other half in a day. It is a truly creepy book, with all the magic of Latin American fiction. Vargas Llosa is an amazing storyteller, with the capacity to leave you thoroughly confused, curious, engaged and amused at the same time. Highly recommended. </span>
  <a data-text-id="15546896306250553174" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


