<span id="freeTextContainer3604475307888448907">I&apos;ll admit to only reading about half of this, but it just never really engaged me. The basic set-up of two Civil Guard officers trying to investigate disappearances in the high Andes amidst the Shining Path rebellion and terror attacks should be extremely compelling. This novel is...not. The main characters barely seem interested in what&apos;s supposed to be the story and I could not cotton to their other ruminations. The scenes were Senderos murder people (and vicunas) are certainly striking, but </span>
  <span id="freeText3604475307888448907" style="display:none">I'll admit to only reading about half of this, but it just never really engaged me. The basic set-up of two Civil Guard officers trying to investigate disappearances in the high Andes amidst the Shining Path rebellion and terror attacks should be extremely compelling. This novel is...not. The main characters barely seem interested in what's supposed to be the story and I could not cotton to their other ruminations. The scenes were Senderos murder people (and vicunas) are certainly striking, but they'r rendered weightless by their disconnect from any other characters or the larger story. Finally, I couldn't help but be turned off by how little Llosa seemed to want understand the people of the Andes. Just generally unengaging and disappointing.</span>
