    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_926844928" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/926844928" />
    <a title="Matt" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16077597-matt"><img alt="Matt" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1582900704p2/16077597.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/926844928?book_show_action=true">May 03, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matt" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matt" href="/user/show/16077597-matt">Matt</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/19294684-tod-in-den-anden">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16077597-matt?shelf=media-ebooks">media-ebooks</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16077597-matt?shelf=eyes-on-the-prize">eyes-on-the-prize</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer926844928" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4182133744525403484">Before I read this novel, my first one by Mario Vargas Llosa, I knew next to nothing about Peru. Now this has changed somewhat. If all of this is true, what is told in this story, Peru must be a very sad country.<br/><br/>Corporal Lituma and his helper TomÃ¡s are being assigned to a remote mining town in the Andes to investigate the mysterious disappearance of three people. The mine is now closed, and the workers, late descendants of the Incas, are now hired to build a road through the mountains. The only </span>
  <span id="freeText4182133744525403484" style="display:none">Before I read this novel, my first one by Mario Vargas Llosa, I knew next to nothing about Peru. Now this has changed somewhat. If all of this is true, what is told in this story, Peru must be a very sad country.<br><br>Corporal Lituma and his helper TomÃ¡s are being assigned to a remote mining town in the Andes to investigate the mysterious disappearance of three people. The mine is now closed, and the workers, late descendants of the Incas, are now hired to build a road through the mountains. The only change takes place in the so-called <i>cantina</i>, a pub, which is operated by the dubious Dionisio and his wife, a fortune teller. From the indios the police officers cannot expect any help, because coastal residents like Lituma are only met with distrust. The indios prefer to believe in the <i>apus</i>, the mountain gods, and the <i>mooqui</i>, goblin-like creatures that live in the mines, and the <i>pishtacos</i>, murderers who kill people for their body fat. In addition, there is a danger of an attack by the fighters of the <i>Sendero Luminoso</i>, the Shining Path, a terrorist guerrilla group, that wants to bring the blessings of communism to the country, and don't hesitate to kill any official representative of the government. Finally, our heroes also have to deal with the rigors of the weather, heavy rains, heat, cold, and landslides. <br><br>Almost the entire story is soaked with subliminal or open violence. As a literary man Llosa refrains from too drastic illustrations and mostly implies, but it is there, this archaic form of violence that lies dormant in possibly every human but wakes up here in the Andes of Peru.<br><br>Unfortunately I don't speak Spanish, so I could not read the original novel, and I think that the translation to German is not particularly successful. Especially the dialogs of the characters seemed to me inappropriate and not consistent. In parts, the words people use seem to come from another time, and just don't fit. By the way, there's a lot of profanity and foul language here, and those of you, who do not like this, should stay away from the book. Fortunately there are also other passages, that I like very much. Those chapters with nested, non-linear narrative, where the past and present flow into one another, are difficult to read but very well crafted and interesting. Also the descriptions of nature and the run-down mining town take the reader exactly there.<br><br>All in all this was a positive reading experience for me and the next book by Llosa is already on my list: <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53972.The_Green_House" title="The Green House by Mario Vargas Llosa" rel="nofollow noopener">The Green House</a> (I made sure it's by another translator).<br><br><a href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <img alt="Creative Commons License" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1380148217i/680962.png" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
</a><br>This work is licensed under a <a href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/" rel="nofollow noopener">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 3.0 Unported License</a>.<br></span>
  <a data-text-id="4182133744525403484" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


